spanGrp.span: transcrbed by ER in January 2008; OK, revised for DoBeS project by WI in March 2013
there is a woman, she walked
daar is 'n vrou, sy het geloop
E repeats /a xng dyaqnn/, but when asked for /ha/ instead of /a/ it was OK
she goes to visit her people
toe gaan kuier sy haar mense
then she turns around, she sees "eqe eqe eqe eqe", someone [the ogre] comes
(...) nǁae ǁaaǁʼng nǀaa "eqe eqe eqe eqe", ǂi saa
toe sy omkyk toe sien sy, "eqe eqe eqe eqe", hy kom
E repeated /ha nǁae .../ but there is a click word at the beginning where she gave /ha/; check again
/ǁaaǁʼng/ acc. to F and E 'omkyk'; there is an [ng] in between, but that might be phonetically conditioned; the same expression appears in Janniejannie (NF071017-02_A.074)
the woman sees an ogre; /eqe/ is the sound of the ogre
the woman spreads her legs; the ogre smells in between
E gave /jy, a/, 'hey, you', but it sounds different
/ǂkxʼoake/ = 'stink, smell bad'; acc. to E this is the same word as 'rotten', but maybe 'rotten' requires the /-a/ suffix => /ǂkxʼoaka/
if I now, if I had now my axe
as ek nou, ng gǂusi ǃoon ki ǃʼoo
as ek nou, as ek nou my byl gehad het
was ist gǂusi; could be an interessting construction; CHECK!!!; cf. also rec. 048 (it is same sentence?)
[gǃusi? ǃoon]/ [gǂuusi ǃoon] oder so ähnlich: F says this means 'as (ek) nou'; /ǃoon/ is 'when' and/or 'now'; what is the first word? check
unclear why this is /ng na/ here
then I would take the axe, then I would chop here, I would chop there, I would chop here, I would take the knife
a nau ǀai ǃʼoo, a nau ǁkxʼoo ki a, a nau ǁkxʼoo ki a, nau ǁkxʼoo ki a nau ǀai nǂona,
daar vat ek die byl, daar kap ek hier, daar kap ek daar, da kap ek hier, da vat ek die mes
/... ki a, ... ki a/: acc. to E something like 'a little bit here, a little bit there'
is it /nau/ or Afrikaans /nou/; F spontaneously translates as 'as ek nou'; 2009: it is probably /nau/ '1.SG.? hu'
I (?would) cut off this rotten piece
daar sny ek hier daardie vrotsels uit
but I don't have them (the axe and the knife) (here with me), I must first go (back home)
maar ng ǁu ki hngke, ng ǁhaa ǂao ǁʼaa",
maar ek het nie nou die goed by my nie, ek moet eers terug huis toe gaan
E repeats /ng ke ǁhaa .../, but I don't hear the /ke/
ther he stands again ? and looks around
daar staan hy weer (van en kyk hier rond,
daar staan hy weer ? en kyk hier rond
as hy so kyk hier, kom hy,
as hy so kyk hier kom hy
hy is so stupid that he leaves behind the axe and the knife
hy is so dom, lat hy die byl en die mes agterlaat,
hy is so dom lat hy die byl en die mes agterlaat
the ogre puts down the axe and the knife that he just had fetched from his house
acc. to E the same word as before; cf. note in Sands 91; the other record sounds like /-ke/!, maybe this is underlying /ǂkxʼaoke-a/
(it is just) a small piece that is rotten
(dis net 'n) klein stukkie wat vrot is
check structure; not sure; does it belong together with the next record?
E only understands first ('stink') and last ('byl') word; check with C
acc. to E there is no [ng]; but it might be the 'and' again, or the nasal before the glottalzed click
E is not sure about this, she thinks it could be/a nou/ or /a nau/ 'ek' (the ogre is still talking)
I chop, I take my knife
a nau ǁkxʼoo, nau ǀai ng nǂona,
toe kap ek, toe vat ek my mes
I throw (it) away, then I eat the meat
ng ǂaqbe ǁʼaa, a nau ain ʘoe,
ek gooi weg, ek nou eet die vleis
E again says the /nou/ is Afrikaans; but could't it be /nau/ again?
I must first go and fetch my axe
ng ǁhaa ǁʼng ǀai ng ǃʼoo,
laat eers my beil loop haal
he runs away, [and when] he runs??
ǁʼannʼa, ha ǃaea nou ǃaea, ha
daar harloop hy, as hy so hardloop
what is /ha/ 3SG here?! postposed SBJ of /ǁʼannʼa/, or SUBJ of /ǃae-a/? listen to recording!
ku ke a ku, ha nǁae
what is the second /ku/? cf. also /ku dyee ku/ ='waar is hy'; same structure here? (SVS)
toe loop maak sy (die boude) af
/a/ sometimes used as 'VOC' after a noun or pronoun, might also be the case here
ng gǂusi ǃoon ki ng nǂona
as ek my mes gehad het
'wenn ich (doch) mein Messer hätte'; the same as rec. 011
then I would chop so, then I would chop so, then I would chop so
a nau ng ǁkxʼoo, a nau ng ǁkxʼoo, a nau ng ǁkxʼoo,
da kap ek so, da kap ek so, da kap ek so
E repeats as /nau ng/ as in preceding records; but maybe it is just /na/ here (she also says 'so' is /nau/, but this is the /ng/)
then I would cut it off
F repeats as /nau/ again, but again it just sounds like /na/
F says this is /ʘoe/, but I am not sure; sounds more like /ǁʼae/ or /ǁae/
E: /a nau kxʼuu sunn/, but why is /kxʼuu/ here 'vat'; E says this is the same word as for 'make', but I think the word starts with a click!
the ogre must go home again, to fetch his axe and knife which he has again not with him
when he comes (back) for the third time, she is in the village
die derde maal dat hy kom, toe is hy in die stat,
the derde mal dat hy kom toe is hy in die stat
when the ogre comes back with his axe and knife for the third time, the woman has reached her homestead
structure?! E sometimes repeats the [e], but sometimes she leaves it out; I have the /X ke e a/ thin also in other texts (sometimes also repeated as /... he a/); should be checked!
the ogre he gets afraid, he does not dare to enter and turns around
check; E sys this is /ki a/, but couldn't it be /ke a/?
what is the /-si/ here? might it be 'coward'?!
the bird has whistled, my story is over and finished
voëltjie het gefluit, uit en gedaan is my storie,
voëltjie het gefluit, ek uit en gedaan is my storie
you hear how ? say in Afrikaans
gǀa tyuu ke ng ku ng ka op Afrikaans,
hoor jy hoe sê hy op Afrikaans
a small piece of meat was rotten
ʼn klein stukkie vleis was vrot
I first thought that would be 'rotten' again, or 'naughty', but I asked E a couple of times, she is sure this is 'vagina'; check with C
